<blockquote>
<p>hard and expensive to build and maintain</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Kant Meters seem to require that SRAs are easy and cheap enough to build that you can miniaturize them and put two of them into a handheld device. They have to be pretty trivial to maintain too, or you wouldn't be using a <em>handheld</em> instrument at all and measuring Humes would be a tricky business done only in the lab with a lot of inherent unreliability due to finicky equipment.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>not to mention that you're having to drain the very reality from dead universes</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That would seem to be an infinite resource.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>they can't just be used willy-nilly to neutralize anomalies.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>But can be used willy-nilly to measure Humes?</p>
<p>I think it it runs the risk of being lazy technobabble that doesn't even look too hard at its own implications. Here, for example, I maintain that it is totally unnecessary, you easily could have given the same conclusion through observations of these entities and what happens if the glamour gland is damaged or removed, IMO.</p>

