			<div class="content" id="post-content-2316046">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Here, for example, I maintain that it is totally unnecessary, you easily could have given the same conclusion through observations of these entities and what happens if the glamour gland is damaged or removes, IMO.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>See, one of the meta things that appeal to me about the Foundation is that we are dealing with the implied supernatural through thoroughly mundane means. Finding the science (or better said, regularities and laws governing) in an anomaly through experimentation is cool. Hey, occassional use of an SCP to contain something else is also cool, because of the implications - we don't quite understand how it works, but it's our best bet in the situation.</p>
<p>Having a generic, completely technobabbley explanation for everything like the Humes are is something I'd expect in the sourcebook of d20 Modern (or another urban fantasy RPG) as an acceptable, if a little cheap way to implement a magic system. Here it strikes me as something that outright devalues a lot of the content we have.</p>

