<p>I think it's amusing how much this potentially clashes with many of the existing fae articles on the site, but I don't find that problematic at all. There is no canon, and there is plenty of room for disagreement or alternate explanations.</p>
<p>As for the -J's&#8230; I've seen something like this explanation somewhere in the forum before. I think it makes sense in some cases, but I apply it selectively if at all. (Edit: It wasn't the forums, it was in <a href="/dressing-up">Resurrection</a>.) I also thought the Humes bit was a bit egregious.</p>
<p>To stop repeating people, I actually liked this a lot because of the world-building in describing the alternate dimension/timeline that they live in. I'm always up for some extradimensional shenanigans, and the details of both the biology and the society were quite well-developed.</p>
<p>I gave this article a +1 and the -J supplement a -1. I understand what purpose it serves and that it's not an actual -J, but like the others posting there, I still think it needs to be funny. The interviewer being named Tamlin was pretty great, but the rest? Not so much.</p>
<p><em>Side thoughts</em>, I guess there's no specific effort to capture or interview -As? Is the Foundation in routine contact with the -B Foundation, as in the Multi-U stories? Do the -Bs also try to prevent the worlds from crossing over, maybe by being discreet in human lands? Purely curious, mind, I don't think these are gaps in the article :)</p>

