														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2314911">
									

<p>I appreciate the work put into the history, and the writing is good, but whenever we tread the &quot;they're dangerous if you think they're dangerous&quot; line, which has been walked before, it has to be done in a super cool or unique way. The fact that the history-altering mechanics are reminiscent of the Daeva doesn't help, and neither does the link to Fae or elves of fiction and myth. Some parts are interesting (inhuman emotions? A relaxed Foundation?) but those aren't the paths that are pursued. Instead we investigate the way that the Foundation is propagating misinformation, which could be a proper avenue for investigation, but it isn't done particularly well.</p>
<p>For example, part of the interest is in the connection to -J articles, which is an amusing meta-twist, until you read the -J article and see that it isn't really like a -J article at all because it isn't very funny. The connection becomes a bit lost when the -J article isn't doing what you specifically say it's supposed to do. The final note in <em>this</em> article is, for the most part, just repeating what could already been inferred from the rest. Do we really need to address why Foundation personnel might believe in fairies?</p>
<p>In my opinion, this article functions like a mishmash of other articles. It's got fairies (Bright's proposal, 2323) that anomalously incorporate into history (140), but only if you believe in them (1055 and others), with a healthy dose of the Foundation deluding itself (1173) while simultaneously missing the best parts of those respective ideas, instead following down a relatively standard path and relying on the -J link for intrigue, a link that doesn't really work because the -J article doesn't function like a -J article should.</p>
<p>With all that in mind, I'm going to novote here and downvote the -J, because the -J is really what needs the most work. If the -J worked as a -J, I'd consider changing my vote because the narrative might work better.</p>

